<br>
What does happen when such set penalty system does get ignored? Guilds start racing for mobs again? <br>
I still think a penalty system encourages laziness. Guilds should be more responsible on keeping track of what they are up for as part of the rotation system as to waiting to be notified. Keep at least some honor in telling the next guild what is going on if not the next guild can always send a tell to the prior guild asking what the status is on mob X. It's a two lane highway. Only thing that scares me is if people do start getting fed up like the above quote statement we will be back to square one, no system at all. Almost sounds like this is the goal intended.<br>
<br>
EDIT: Oh yeah lets not forget either. Euro guilds are much stronger today than a year ago capable of setting up on average 6 hours prior to state side guilds. Ignoring the rot system might actually leave you less to play with Merloc. I don't speak on behalf of my guild on this matter its just my opinion. My Air force recruiter told me 5 years ago that once I sign up to be careful what I ask for. I believe this goes for everything and we should all do the same.<br>
